[3] Greece
Date: Tue 14 Feb 2006
From: "Mary Marshall" <tropical.forestry@btinternet.com>
Source: Reuters Foundation AlertNet, Tue 14 Feb 2006 [edited]
<http://www.alertnet.org/thenews/newsdesk/L14698550.htm>

Greece: 2 Suspected Cases Discharged after Testing Negative
-------------------------------------------------------------
The Greek Health Authorities stated on Tuesday [14 Feb 2006] that a
hunter suspected of having contracted avian influenza had tested
negative, as authorities enlisted the country's powerful Orthodox
Church to educate farmers about how to prevent infection.
Since re-emerging in Asia in late 2003, avian influenza has killed at
least 91 people in Asia and the Middle East and spread west across
the globe as far as Sicily and Nigeria. [As of 13 Feb 2006, however,
human cases have been recorded in seven countries only: Cambodia (4
cases and 4 deaths), China (12 cases and 8 deaths), Indonesia (25
cases and 18 deaths), Iraq (1 case and 1 death), Thailand (22 cases
and 14 deaths), Turkey (12 cases and 4 deaths), and Viet Nam (93
cases and 42 deaths). - Mod.CP]
Over the weekend, health authorities confirmed the presence of the
highly pathogenic H5N1 strain of the virus in 3 swans in northern
Greece, reporting, with Italy, the 1st cases of infected migratory
birds on European Union soil. Two people were also being tested after
coming into contact with suspect poultry and developing flu-like
symptoms. A 15-year-old boy was released on Monday [13 Feb 2006]
after twice testing negative. The 29-year-old hunter was released
from quarantine on Tuesday [14 Feb 2006], after he tested negative
too. "The Centre for Infectious Diseases Control announced that both
primary and secondary laboratory tests for the H5N1 strain are
negative," the ministry said in a statement.
Health officials have resorted to the Greek Orthodox church to step
up the fight against bird flu. In a letter to church leaders, the
Health Ministry asked priests to spread the word on precautions
farmers should take to prevent infection by reading an advice
bulletin to worshippers. It includes measures such as regular
handwashing, a warning against approaching wild or free range birds,
and a request that any dead poultry be reported immediately to the authorities.
